<li id="cite_note-27"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="Rosh_Hashanah#cite_ref-27">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Halakha" title="Halakha">Jewish Law</a> permits the Shofar to be blown in the presence of a rabbinical court called the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sanhedrin" title="Sanhedrin">Sanhedrin</a>, which had not existed since ancient times. A recent group of Orthodox rabbis in <a href="Israel" title="Israel">Israel</a> claiming to constitute a <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modern_attempts_to_revive_the_Sanhedrin" title="Modern attempts to revive the Sanhedrin">modern Sanhedrin</a> held, for the first time in many years, an Orthodox shofar-blowing on Shabbat for Rosh Hashanah in 2006. <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://thesanhedrin.net/forums/viewtopic.php?t=355">TheSanhedrin.net: Shofar Blowing on Shabbat</a> (translation of <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.haaretz.co.il/hasite/spages/766399.html">Haaretz</a> <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20090126203729/http://www.haaretz.co.il/hasite/spages/766399.html">Archived</a> January 26, 2009, at the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wayback_Machine" title="Wayback Machine">Wayback Machine</a> article)</span>
